            std::cout << num << "\t\t\t" << (num * num) << std::endl;
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

**Explanation of change:** The `if (num % 2 == 0)` condition is inserted inside the `for` loop. The modulo operator (`%`) returns the remainder of a division. If `num % 2` is `0`, it means `num` is perfectly divisible by 2, and thus it is an even number. The `cout` statement (which prints the number and its square) will only execute when this condition is true, effectively filtering out odd numbers.

